Rationale.RationaleText: Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 Surgery Integumentary System, it is a misuse of therapeutic injection or aspiration CPT codes to report administration of local anesthesia for a procedure. For example, it is a misuse of CPT codes 10160 (Puncture aspiration), 20500-20501 (Injection of sinus tract), 20526-20553 (Injection of carpal tunnel, tendon sheath, ligament, trigger points, etc.), 20600-20611 (Arthrocentesis) to report administration of local anesthetic. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 Paragraph I. Grafts and Flaps, debridement of a skin wound (e.g., CPT codes 11000, 11042-11047, 97597, 97598) prior to a graft/skin substitute is included in the skin graft/skin substitute procedure (CPT codes 15050-15278) and shall not be reported separately. If the recipient site requires excision of open wounds, burn eschar, or scar or incisional release of scar contracture, CPT codes 15002-15005 may be separately reportable for certain types of skin grafts/skin substitutes. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT Assistant October 2012 page 3 Treatment of Burns, debridement codes 11000-11047 should not be reported to describe debridement of burn wounds. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, Removal of prosthetic material or mesh, abdominal wall for infection (eg, for chronic or recurrent mesh infection or necrotizing soft tissue infection) (List separately in addition to code for primary procedure) is an add-on code reported for removal of unincorporated or infected areas mesh only. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, in 11010, the physician surgically removes foreign matter and contaminated or devitalized skin and other tissue in and around the site of an open fracture or open dislocation. Debridement reported with this service includes prolonged cleansing of the wound; removal of all foreign or dead tissue or material, using forceps, scissors, scalpel, or other instruments; exploration of all injured soft tissue, including tendons, ligaments, and nerves; and irrigation of all tissue layers (skin and subcutaneous tissue). This was not described in the operative report submitted for review and therefore, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, in 11011, the physician surgically removes foreign matter and contaminated or devitalized skin, subcutaneous tissue, muscle fascia, and muscle, in and around the site of an open fracture or open dislocation. Debridement reported with this service includes prolonged cleansing of the wound; removal of all foreign or dead tissue or material using forceps, scissors, scalpel, or other instruments; exploration of all injured soft tissue, including tendons, ligaments, and nerves; and irrigation of all tissue layers (skin, subcutaneous tissue, muscle fascia, and muscle). This was not described in the operative report submitted for review and therefore, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, in 11012, the physician surgically removes foreign matter and contaminated or devitalized skin, subcutaneous tissue, muscle fascia, muscle and bone, in and around the site of an open fracture or open dislocation. Debridement reported with this service includes prolonged cleansing of the wound; removal of all foreign or dead tissue or material using forceps, scissors, scalpel, or other instruments; exploration of all injured soft tissue, including tendons, ligaments, and nerves; and irrigation of all tissue layers (skin, subcutaneous tissue, muscle fascia, muscle, and bone). This was not described in the operative report submitted for review and therefore, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, when reporting debridement of a single wound, the deepest level of tissue removed determines the correct code. For {ServiceCode}, the method of debridement and/or tissue level of debridement into subcutaneous tissue (includes epidermis and dermis, if performed) is not described in the operative report submitted for review and is therefore denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, when reporting debridement of a single wound, the deepest level of tissue removed determines the correct code. For {ServiceCode}, the method of debridement and/or tissue level of debridement into muscle and/or fascia (includes epidermis, dermis, and subcutaneous tissue, muscle, fascia or bone if performed) is not described in the operative report submitted for review and is therefore denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Fractures, Dislocations, and Casting/Splinting/Strapping, debridement CPT codes and grafting CPT codes shall not be reported with a casting/splinting/strapping CPT code for the same anatomic area. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Fractures, Dislocations, and Casting/Splinting/Strapping, debridement CPT codes (e.g., 11042-11047, 97597) and grafting CPT codes (e.g., 15040-15776) shall not be reported with a casting/splinting/strapping CPT code (e.g., 29445, 29580, 29581) for the same anatomic area. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, when reporting debridement of a single wound, the deepest level of tissue removed determines the correct code. For {ServiceCode}, the method of debridement and/or tissue level of debridement into muscle and/or fascia (includes epidermis, dermis, and subcutaneous tissue, if performed) was not described in the operative report submitted for review and is therefore denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual, Chapter 4, Section H (General Policy Statement #11): Debridement of tissue in the surgical field of another musculoskeletal procedure is not separately reportable. For example, debridement of muscle and/or bone (CPT codes 11043-11044, 11046-11047) associated with excision of a tumor of bone is not separately reportable. Similarly, debridement of tissue (e.g., CPT codes 11042, 11045, 11720-11721, 97597, 97598) superficial to, but in the surgical field, of a musculoskeletal procedure is not separately reportable. However, debridement of tissue at the site of an open fracture or dislocation may be reported separately with CPT codes 11010-11012. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and CPT code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT, when reporting debridement of a single wound, the deepest level of tissue removed determines the correct code. For {ServiceCode}, the method of debridement and/or tissue level of debridement into bone (includes epidermis, dermis, subcutaneous tissue, muscle and/or fascia, if performed) is not described in the operative report submitted for review and is therefore denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the request for {ServiceCode} Debridement, each additional 20 sq cm, or part thereof is not described in the operative report submitted for review and is therefore denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, when reporting debridement of a single wound, the deepest level of tissue removed determines the correct code. For {ServiceCode}, the method of debridement and/or tissue level of debridement into muscle and/or fascia (includes epidermis, dermis, and subcutaneous tissue, muscle and/ or fascia and bone if performed) was not described in the operative report submitted for review and is therefore denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, Paring or cutting of benign hyperkeratotic lesion (eg, corn or callus); single lesion is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, Paring or cutting of benign hyperkeratotic lesion (eg, corn or callus); 2 to 4 lesions is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, requires documentation of the number of benign hyperkeratotic lesions treated. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, Paring or cutting of benign hyperkeratotic lesion (eg, corn or callus); more than 4 lesions is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI policy Manual Chapter 3 Surgery of the Integumentary system, the CPT codes for lesion removal includes the procurement of tissue from the same lesion by biopsy at the same patient encounter. CPT codes 11102-11107 (biopsy of skin) shall not be reported separately.

Per CPT, {ServiceCode} Shaving of epidermal or dermal lesion, single lesion, scalp, neck, hands, feet, genitalia includes local anesthesia in a sensate patient unless medically contraindicated, partial thickness excision by horizontal slicing and wound cauterization. This is not described in the clinical documentation submitted for review. The procedure described is paring or cutting of benign hyperkeratotic lesion (eg, corn or callus). As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied and code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT, {ServiceCode} Shaving of epidermal or dermal lesion, single lesion, scalp, neck, hands, feet, genitalia includes local anesthesia in a sensate patient unless medically contraindicated, partial thickness excision by horizontal slicing and wound cauterization. This is not described in the clinical documentation submitted for review. The procedure described is paring or cutting of benign hyperkeratotic lesion (eg, corn or callus). As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, Hidradenitis is a chronic relapsing disease that occurs in tissue where apocrine glands are found. Localized nodules develop from occlusion of the apocrine ducts. Recurrence of the lesions may produce superimposed infections, recurrent abscesses with or without sinus formation, and scarring. The physician performs an excision of the affected skin and subcutaneous tissue . This was not described in the operative report submitted for review. Therefore, the requested for {ServiceCode} Excision of skin and subcutaneous tissue for hidradenitis, axillary is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, Hidradenitis is a chronic relapsing disease that occurs in tissue where apocrine glands are found. Localized nodules develop from occlusion of the apocrine ducts. Recurrence of the lesions may produce superimposed infections, recurrent abscesses with or without sinus formation, and scarring. The physician performs an excision of the affected skin and subcutaneous tissue . This was not described in the operative report submitted for review. Therefore, the requested for {ServiceCode} Excision of skin and subcutaneous tissue for hidradenitis, axillary is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant March 2014, CPT 21011-21016, CPT 21920-21936, CPT 21552 - 21558 are histologically specific. CPT restricts the use of code to lesions of non-cutaneous origin, such as sarcomas and lipomas. These codes are NOT appropriate for epidermoid cysts, papillomas, melanomas, squamous and basal cell carcinomas. For excision/radical resection of tumors of cutaneous origin, see codes 11620–11646. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant April 2010 page 3, for radical resection of tumors of cutaneous origin (e.g., melanoma), report the appropriate code from the 11600-11646 series. Appropriate code choice is based on the measurement of the tumor plus its margin made at the time of excision. Thus, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, requested service code 11721 Debridement of nails by any method(s); 6 or more is not documented. The number of nails treated needs to be documented in the procedure note. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, in {ServiceCode} Avulsion of nail plate, partial or complete, a digital nerve block is used to numb the top of the digit unless patient is insensate or medically contraindicated. The physician bluntly dissects the nail plate from the nail bed. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, code 11755 Biopsy of nail unit (eg, plate, bed, matrix, hyponychium, proximal and lateral nail folds) (separate procedure), is usually a component of a more complex service and is not identified separately. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, in 11765 Wedge excision of skin of nail fold (eg, for ingrown toenail), The physician excises a wedge of restrictive skin in the nail fold to free an ingrown nail. Local anesthesia is included in this service unless patient is insensate or medically contraindicated. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 Surgery of the Integumentary System, CPT codes 11900-11901 describe intralesional injections of non-chemotherapeutic agents. CPT codes 96405-96406 describe intralesional injections of chemotherapeutic agents. Two intralesional injection codes shall not be reported together unless separate lesions are injected with different agents, in which case modifier 59 or XS may be used. It is a misuse of CPT codes 11900, 11901, 96405, or 96406 to report injection of local anesthetic prior to another procedure on the lesion(s). Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual, Chapter 8, closure/repair of a surgical incision is included in the global surgical package. Wound repair CPT codes 12001-13153 shall not be reported separately to describe closure of surgical incisions for procedures with global surgery indicators of 000, 010, 090, or MMM. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, Complex closure of a wound requires additional special treatment, such as the use of stent dressings, retention sutures, or extensive revision, which may involve removing sizable portions of skin or extensive undermining of the skin to loosen the tissues to close a defect. In addition, at least one of the following is required: 1) exposure of bone, cartilage, tendon, or a named neurovascular structure; 2) extensive undermining that is at least one entire edge of the defect but a distance greater than or equal to the maximum width of the defect, measured perpendicular to the closure line; 3) involvement of free margins of helical rim, nostril rim, or vermilion border in which retention sutures are placed. This was not documented and the request for {ServiceCode} Complex closure is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code (ServiceCode) (Adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement) is not described in the operative report submitted for review. Per CPT Guidelines, "undermining alone of adjacent tissues to achieve closure, without additional incisions does not constitute adjacent tissue transfer." In addition, per NCCI Policy Chapter 3, "extensively undermining of adjacent tissue to achieve closure of a wound or defect may constitute complex repair, not tissue transfer and rearrangement. Tissue transfer and rearrangement requires that adjacent tissue be incised and carried over to close a wound or defect." This degree of surgery is not described in the operative report. Thus, the request for (ServiceCode) is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code (SeviceCode), (Adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement) is not described in the operative report submitted for review. Per CPT Assistant April 2014, "where there is an excess of tissue (dog ear). Therefore, no tissue transfer is necessary to reconstruct the area." This degree of surgery is not described in the operative report. As such, the request for (ServiceCode) is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant April 2017, the use of CPT 14001 – 14302 for partial breast reconstruction following lumpectomy requires documentation of specific criteria. These are defect the size, dissection through the breast parenchyma in order to create a pedicle flap of breast tissue, transposition of the flap into the defect, preservation of vascularity, the dimensions of the tissue mobilized, and the technique for transfer of the tissue into the defect. Undermining of the breast tissue off the pectoralis major muscle alone or undermining tissue within the breast parenchyma to advance tissue for primary repair is not considered adjacent tissue transfer and would be bundled with the partial mastectomy code. The obliteration of dead space is inherent in the partial mastectomy code. Therefore, adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement is not described and thus requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT Assistant February 2015 page 10, breast reconstruction procedures include adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement procedures, if performed. An adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement procedure may be reported on the same day as a breast reconstruction procedure if the adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement is performed at a different site unrelated to the breast reconstruction procedure. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, These codes do not apply when direct closure or rearrangement of traumatized tissue incidentally results in these Adjacent Tissue Transfer configurations. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} Adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, undermining alone of adjacent tissues to achieve closure, without additional incisions does not constitute adjacent tissue transfer. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} Adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement is denied as "Not Documented."

In addition, per NCCI Policy Chapter 3, "extensively undermining of adjacent tissue to achieve closure of a wound or defect may constitute complex repair, not tissue transfer and rearrangement. Tissue transfer and rearrangement requires that adjacent tissue be incised and carried over to close a wound or defect." This degree of surgery is not described in the operative report. Thus, the request for (ServiceCode) is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, undermining alone of adjacent tissues to achieve closure, without additional incisions does not constitute adjacent tissue transfer. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and complex repair code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT Guidelines, "The excision of a benign (11400-11446) or malignant lesion (11600-11646), is not reported separately with codes 14000-14302." In addition, per NCCI Policy Chapter 3, "Adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement procedures include excision (CPT codes 11400-11646) and repair (12001-13160). Thus, CPT codes 11400-11646 and 12001-13160 shall not be reported separately with CPT codes 14000-14350 for the same lesion or injury." Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3, an adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement procedure may be reported on the same day as a breast reconstruction procedure if the adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement is performed at a different site unrelated to the breast reconstruction procedure. Therefore, adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement is not described and thus the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per the Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons April 2017 Page 56, CPT codes for adjacent tissue transfer (14000–14302) may not be reported with a hernia repair, even if extensive mobilization of skin and adipose tissue is performed. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per the Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons April 2017, CPT codes for adjacent tissue transfer (14000–14302) may not be reported with a hernia repair, even if extensive mobilization of skin and adipose tissue is performed. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} Adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, excision of an ellipse of skin, with subsequent closure that incidentally results in these configurations, does not constitute an adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement. When these codes are used to report repair of traumatic wounds, the procedure must have been previously planned and developed by the physician to affect the repair. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} Adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement is denied as "Not Documented."

Per AAOS Code-X/GSD, AAOS Bulletin August 2005 and American Society of Plastic Surgeons Plastic Surgery News CPT Corner February 2016, CPT Assistant March 2021; it is inappropriate to report a flap/graft service from the integumentary system for the procedure described in the submitted operative report. Local tissue rearrangement is considered inclusive to primary carpal tunnel releases. Utilization of adjacent tissue transfer codes is appropriate in a carpal tunnel revision. as such adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement is not described and thus the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, {ServiceCode} (Adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement) is not described in the operative report submitted for review. Therefore, the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Guidelines, "undermining alone of adjacent tissues to achieve closure, without additional incisions does not constitute adjacent tissue transfer." In addition, per NCCI Policy Chapter 3, "extensively undermining of adjacent tissue to achieve closure of a wound or defect may constitute complex repair, not tissue transfer and rearrangement. Tissue transfer and rearrangement requires that adjacent tissue be incised and carried over to close a wound or defect." This degree of surgery is not described in the operative report. Thus, the request for (ServiceCode) is denied as "Not Documented."

Per American Society of Plastic Surgeons CPT Corner Article from Plastic Surgery News February 2008, to report the requested service code, 14301 Adjacent tissue transfer or rearrangement, any area; defect 30.1 sq. cm to 60.0 sq. cm, an incision must be made and a secondary defect created and documented. This is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, in code {ServiceCode}, the physician transfers or rearranges adjacent tissue of any area to repair traumatic or surgical wounds. The primary advantage of an adjacent tissue transfer is that an essential part of the flap remains connected to an intact and anatomically-specific vascular pedicle. This same vascular pedicle provides continuous vascular supply to the tissue flap that has been transferred to fill the defect of the excised soft tissue. The operative report submitted for review, does not describe the requisite level of detail of the dissection and development of the specific vascular pedicle, which is a necessary component of the tissue transfer/rearrangement. Thus, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant February 2013 page 16, CPT codes 15002 -15005 require surgical preparation of a wound or creation of recipient site by excision of open wounds, burn eschar, or scar (including subcutaneous tissues), or incisional release of scar contracture. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} excisional preparation is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant January 2012 page 6, the following guidelines apply to all three subsections (Surgical Preparation, Autografts, and Skin Substitute Grafts): Debridement is considered a separate procedure only when gross contamination requires prolonged cleansing, when appreciable amounts of devitalized or contaminated tissue are removed, or when debridement is carried out separately without immediate primary closure. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} Surgical preparation or creation of recipient site by excision of open wounds, burn eschar, or scar (including subcutaneous tissues), or incisional release of scar contracture, is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant January 2012 page 6, when a wound is left to heal by secondary intention, it is not appropriate to report codes 15002-15005 for the removal of nonviable tissue/debris in a chronic wound (eg, venous or diabetic). Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant October 2012 page 3 Treatment of Burns, CPT codes 15002-15005 describe burn and wound preparation by incisional or excisional release of scar contracture, which results in an open wound that requires a skin graft. Surgical preparation codes 15002-15005 for skin replacement surgery describe the initial services related to preparing a clean and viable wound surface for the placement of an autograft, flap, or skin substitute graft, or negative pressure wound therapy. The excisional preparation is coded once per recipient area, regardless of the size of the excision. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant October 2012 page 3 Treatment of Burns, when surgical preparation codes 15002-15005 are used to describe a tangential excision of a burn wound in preparation for skin grafting, it is important to note that although the code is always used in combination with a skin graft code, this may be a staged procedure (delayed) in which the preparation of the recipient site is performed on one date, while the graft procedure is performed on a different date. In these cases, modifier 58, Staged or Related Procedure or Service by the Same Physician During the Postoperative Period, is appended to the grafting procedure code performed during the global period. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and code {SuggestedCode}, appended with modifier 58 is suggested.

Per CPT, in all cases, for codes 15002-15005, appreciable nonviable tissue is removed to treat a burn, traumatic wound or a necrotizing infection. The clean wound bed may also be created by incisional release of a scar contracture resulting in a surface defect from separation of tissue. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} excisional preparation is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant January 2012, page 6, when a wound is left to heal by secondary intention, it is not appropriate to report codes 15002-15005 for the removal of nonviable tissue/debris in a chronic wound (eg, venous or diabetic). Instead, use the appropriate active wound management codes (97597, 97598) and the debridement codes (11042-11047) for this service. When treating necrotizing soft tissue infections in specific anatomic locations, use codes 11004-11008. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and complex repair code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 Surgery of the Integumentary System, debridement of a skin wound (e.g., CPT codes 11000, 11042-11047, 97597, 97598) prior to a graft/skin substitute is included in the skin graft/skin substitute procedure (CPT codes 15050-15278) and shall not be reported separately. If the recipient site requires excision of open wounds, burn eschar, or scar or incisional release of scar contracture, CPT codes 15002-15005 may be separately reportable for certain types of skin grafts/skin substitutes. However, CPT Assistant October 2012 Treatment of Burns, states the excisional preparation is coded once per recipient area, regardless of the size of the excision. Thus, the request for {ServiceCode} excisional preparation is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}, as excisional preparation has previously been reported for this recipient area.

Per CPT, debridement and preparation of a wound is considered inclusive to graft application if performed on the day of application. Minimal wound preparation should be necessary on the day of graft application. Simple cleaning and tissue debridement and current graft removal are considered inclusive to the full-thickness and split-thickness autografts, as well as application of skin substitute grafts. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 Paragraph I. Grafts and Flaps, debridement of a skin wound (e.g., CPT codes 11000, 11042-11047, 97597, 97598) prior to a graft/skin substitute is included in the skin graft/skin substitute procedure (CPT codes 15050-15278) and shall not be reported separately. Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 Paragraph I. Grafts and Flaps, debridement of a skin wound (e.g., CPT codes 11000, 11042-11047, 97597, 97598) prior to a graft/skin substitute is included in the skin graft/skin substitute procedure (CPT codes 15050-15278) and shall not be reported separately. If the recipient site requires excision of open wounds, burn eschar, or scar or incisional release of scar contracture, CPT codes 15002-15005 may be separately reportable for certain types of skin grafts/skin substitutes. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and complex repair code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT, debridement and preparation of a wound is inclusive to graft application if performed on the day of application.   Minimal wound preparation should be necessary on the day of graft application. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 Surgery of the Integumentary System, The primary graft/skin substitute codes (e.g., 15100, 15120, 15200, 15220) are mutually exclusive since only one type of graft/skin substitute can be utilized at an anatomic site. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} debridement and/or surgical preparation is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 Surgery of the Integumentary System, The primary graft/skin substitute CPT codes 15100-15116, 15120-15157, 15200-15261, and 15271-15278 are mutually exclusive since only one type of graft/skin substitute can be utilized at an anatomic site. If multiple sites require different types of grafts/skin substitutes, the different graft/skin substitute CPT codes should be reported with anatomic modifiers or modifier 59 or XS to indicate the different sites. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, codes 15271-15278 are reported for application of a skin substitute to an open wound; not for augmentation of healing of bone, tendon, muscle or nerve. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} Application of skin substitute graft is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the introduction to the Skin Replacement Surgery section of the CPT codebook states: "The graft is anchored using the individual's choice of fixation. When services are performed in the office, routine dressing supplies are not reported separately" (CPT 2021; p 106). "These codes are not to be reported for application of non-graft wound dressings (eg, gel, powder, ointment, foam, liquid) or injected skin substitutes. Application of non-graft wound dressings is not separately reportable. Removal of current graft and/or simple cleansing of the wound is included, when performed" (CPT 2021; p 107). Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, the introduction to the Skin Replacement Surgery section of the CPT codebook states: "The graft is anchored using the individual's choice of fixation. When services are performed in the office, routine dressing supplies are not reported separately" (CPT 2021; p 106).

Per CPT, CPT Assistant October 2013; the requested service code, 15777, is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented."  Note that "Code 15777 is for soft tissue reinforcement and is only intended for use with the Integumentary System section of codes. Therefore, it is not appropriate to report code 15777 in conjunction with codes for various procedures outside the Integumentary System, such as pericardium repair, hernia repairs, arteriotomy/venotomy repair, tendon repair, tonsillar repair following tonsillectomy, or any soft tissue reinforcement of organs (such as liver, kidney, pleura, peritoneum, gallbladder)."

Per CPT, skin substitutes are used as a temporary measure to close wounds and provide a barrier against infection and fluid loss, reduce pain, and promote healing of underlying tissues until a permanent graft can be applied. As such, the request for CPT code 15275 Application of skin substitute graft to face, scalp, eyelids, mouth, neck, ears, orbits, genitalia, hands, feet, and/or multiple digits, total wound surface area up to 100 sq. cm; first 25 sq. cm or less wound surface area is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant March 2010 page 4, CPT codes 15570-15576: The physician forms a direct or tubed pedicle flap to reconstruct traumatic defects. A pedicle flap of full-thickness skin and subcutaneous tissue that retains its supporting blood vessels is developed in the donor area. A tubed pedicle flap maintains two vascular ends and the cut edges of the raised flap are sutured together to form a tube. The flap may be rotated or transferred to the defect area and sutured to the recipient bed in layers. The physician closes the harvest region in layers or covers it with a split-thickness skin graft. These flaps are used for non-adjacent tissue transfers involving skin and subcutaneous tissues. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} Formation of direct or tubed pedicle flap, with or without transfer, is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant March 2010 page 4 and December 2012 page 6, CPT code 15650 is reported for the intermediate transfer of any pedicle flap at any location. If the transfer of the pedicle flap to the recipient site is performed during the same procedure as the formation of the pedicle, the intermediate transfer code 15650 is not reported. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} for the intermediate transfer of any pedicle flap is "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant April 2018 page 10, CPT code 15733 Muscle, myocutaneous, or fasciocutaneous flap; head and neck with named vascular pedicle (ie, buccinators, genioglossus, temporalis, masseter, sternocleidomastoid, levator scapulae). Single screw and washer systems that are placed to prevent graft or cage kick-out cannot withstand a biomechanical load, if they are placed as a stand-alone device. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, CPT codes have been written as precisely as possible to not only describe a specific procedure but to also avoid describing similar procedures which are already defined by other CPT codes. When a CPT code is reported, the physician or non-physician provider must have performed all of the services noted in the descriptor unless the descriptor states otherwise. (Occasionally, a CPT code descriptor will identify certain services that may or may not be included.) A CPT code should not be reported out of the context for which it was intended. When the procedure described by CPT code 30930 Fracture nasal inferior turbinate(s), therapeutic is reported with the procedure described by CPT code 30802 Ablation, soft tissue of inferior turbinates, unilateral or bilateral, any method (eg, electrocautery, radiofrequency ablation, or tissue volume reduction); intramural (ie, submucosal), reporting the former code represents a misuse of this code, and separate payment is not allowed. As such, CPT code 30930 is denied as inclusive to 30802.

Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per American Academy of Otolaryngology Guidelines, when nasal endoscopy is performed at the same session, with the same scope as flexible laryngoscopy, they both may not be reported. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 5 D. Cardiovascular System, Operative ablation procedures (CPT codes 33250-33266) include cardioversion as an integral component of the procedures. Per CPT, for a limited operative tissue ablation and reconstruction of atria (33257), also referred to as a modified Maze procedure, an incision is made into the left or right atrium. A combination of surgical incision and/or energy sources, such as heat, microwave, laser, ultrasound, or cryoprobe, is used to create lesions that will heal into scars that disrupt conduction. In 33258 and 33259, an extensive operative tissue ablation and reconstruction of the atria is performed. In these extensive procedures, the right and/or left atrial tissue and/or atrial septum is treated as described in 33257, and additional operative ablation involving the atrioventricular annulus is performed. In any of these procedures, the left atrial appendage may be excised or isolated. In 33259, lines are placed for cardiopulmonary bypass. The operative report submitted for review does not support the request for {ServiceCode}. As such, {ServiceCode} is denied and {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT, for a limited operative tissue ablation and reconstruction of atria (33257), also referred to as a modified Maze procedure, an incision is made into the left or right atrium. In these extensive procedures, the right and/or left atrial tissue and/or atrial septum is treated as described in 33257, and additional operative ablation involving the atrioventricular annulus is performed. Per AMA Principles of CPT Coding 9th edition 2017, page 226, CPT codes 33510-33516 (Coronary artery bypass, vein only) and 33517-33523 (Coronary artery bypass, using venous graft(s) and arterial graft(s)) include the work for open procurement of the saphenous vein graft; therefore, these procedures should not be reported as a separate service or cosurgery. When only arterial grafting is performed, only one code in the range of CPT codes 33533-33536 may be reported. Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Cardiovascular System, coronary artery bypass procedures using venous grafts (CPT codes 33510-33523) include procurement of the venous graft(s) as an integral component of the procedure. Per CPT Assistant November 2020 Volume 30 Issue 11, do not report 33745, 33746 in conjunction with 93530, 93531, 93532, 93533. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, a leak, called an endoleak, may occur at the proximal fixation sites of a grafted descending thoracic aorta defect through the body of the graft or from patent arteries within the defect and may require endovascular repair. A proximal extension prosthesis is placed endovascularly to repair an endoleak in a grafted descending thoracic aortic aneurysm, pseudoaneurysm, dissection, penetrating ulcer, intramural hematoma, or traumatic disruption. The target site is identified by aortography and the proper extension prosthesis is selected. Report 33883 for an initial proximal extension and 33884 for each additional proximal extension. These codes include all device introduction, manipulation, positioning, and deployment. Balloon angioplasty and/or stent deployment is not reported separately. Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, a leak, called an endoleak, may occur at the distal fixation sites of a previously grafted descending thoracic aorta defect through the body of the graft or from patent arteries within the defect and may require endovascular repair. One or more distal extension prosthesis modules are placed endovascularly to the level of the celiac artery to repair an endoleak in a previously grafted descending thoracic aortic aneurysm, pseudoaneurysm, dissection, penetrating ulcer, intramural hematoma, or traumatic disruption. The target site is identified by aortography and the proper extension prosthesis is selected. This code includes all device introduction, manipulation, positioning, and deployment. Balloon angioplasty and/or stent deployment is not reported separately. Do not report 33886 with 33880 or 33881. Report 33886 once, regardless of the number of modules deployed. Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, procedure code 33915 Pulmonary artery embolectomy; without cardiopulmonary bypass is only done for patients who are in extremis following a pulmonary artery embolism. Survival is low. Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 I. Cardiovascular Services, cardiac catheterization, percutaneous coronary artery interventional procedures (angioplasty, atherectomy, or stenting), and internal cardioversion include insertion of a needle and/or catheter, infusion, fluoroscopy and ECG rhythm strips (e.g., CPT codes 36000, 36140, 36160, 36200-36248, 36410, 96360-96376, 76000, 93040-93042). Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, because the placement of peripheral vascular access devices is integral to intravenous infusions and injections, the CPT codes for placement of these devices are not separately reportable. Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 I. Cardiovascular Services, Cardiovascular stress tests include insertion of needle and/or catheter, infusion/injection (pharmacologic stress tests) and ECG strips (e.g., CPT codes 36000, 36410, 96360-96376, 93000-93010, 93040-93042). These services shall not be reported separately. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

In CPT codes 36215-36218 Selective catheter placement, arterial system, the catheter may pass through the first order vessel into a second order thoracic or brachiocephalic artery. In 36215, the catheter remains in a first order artery. In 36216, the catheter travels further to a second order artery. Per CPT, code the highest order vessel cannulated, but not any lesser order vessels cannulated in the approach. Additional second and/or third order arterial catheterizations within the same family of arteries supplied by a single first order artery should be reported with 36218. Additional first order or higher catheterizations in vascular families supplied by a first order vessel different from a previously selected and coded family should be separately coded using the conventions described above. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and selective catheterization code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

In CPT codes 36215-36218 Selective catheter placement, arterial system, the catheter may pass through the first order vessel into a second order thoracic or brachiocephalic artery. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

In CPT codes 36215-36218 Selective catheter placement, arterial system, the catheter may pass through the first order vessel into a second order thoracic or brachiocephalic artery. Selective vascular catheterizations should be coded to include introduction and all lesser order selective catheterizations used in the approach (eg, the description for a selective right middle cerebral artery catheterization includes the introduction and placement catheterization of the right common and internal carotid arteries). As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, code 36221 is reported for non-selective arterial catheter placement in the thoracic aorta and diagnostic imaging of the aortic arch and great vessel origins.
