The provider must be solely dedicated to monitoring the neurophysiological tests and available to intervene if necessary. Report 95940 for each set of 15 minutes that the monitoring is done from within the operating room in a one-on-one setting. The neuromonitoring report does not establish that the qualified neuromonitoring health care provider was present in the operating room. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, do not use CPT codes 95940–95941 to report automated intraoperative neurophysiology monitoring that do not require continuous professional monitoring and diagnostic interpretation. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, is an Add-on code. Report 95940 and 95941 in addition to the code for the study that is being performed: 92653, 95860-95870, 95907-95913, or 95925-95939. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} cannot be approved without approval of one or more appropriate primary codes. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 L. Neurology and Neuromuscular Procedures, Intraoperative neurophysiology testing shall not be reported by the physician performing an operative or anesthesia procedure since it is included in the global package. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 L. Neurology and Neuromuscular Procedures, CPT code 95940 describes continuous intraoperative neurophysiology monitoring in the operating room requiring one on one monitoring and personal attendance. HCPCS code G0453 describes continuous intraoperative neurophysiology monitoring for a single patient from outside the operating room (remote or nearby). The unit of service for each of these procedures is "each 15 minutes." A physician shall not report both of these procedures for the same time period. If the 2 procedures are reported for the same date of service for the same patient, the time period for each procedure must be distinct and not overlapping with the time period for the other procedure. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, report code 95941 Continuous intraoperative neurophysiology monitoring (IONM), from outside the operating room (remote or nearby) or for monitoring of more than one case while in the operating room, per hour. Do not report code 95941 if monitoring lasts 30 minutes or less for any one case. Thus, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 L. Neurology and Neuromuscular Procedures, CPT code 95941 describes continuous intraoperative neurophysiology monitoring from outside the operating room (remote or nearby) or monitoring of more than one case while in the operating room. This code is not valid for Medicare practitioner services. It is a packaged service under Medicare Hospital OPPS (Outpatient Prospective Payment System). As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant December 2014 page 19, CPT code 95955 was created for the service of sending a senior EEG technologist to the operating room to run the recording, with the physician reading the record after the recording has taken place. The neurophysiology monitoring report describes real time interpretation of an EEG when a patient is not awake during the recording. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant December 2014 page 19, CPT code 95955 was created for the service of sending a senior EEG technologist to the operating room to run the recording, with the physician reading the record after the recording has taken place. The neurophysiology monitoring report describes real time interpretation of an EEG when a patient is not awake during the recording. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and CPT code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

As per CPT Assistant October 2018 page 8 Coding Brief: Reporting Percutaneous Implantation of Neurostimulator Electrode Arrays Codes: Instructions in the revised guidelines also note that electronic analysis (95970) performed at the time the device is implanted should not be reported separately in conjunction with the implantation procedure because test stimulation to confirm correct target site placement of electrode array(s) and/or to confirm the functional status of the system is inherent to the implantation procedure. As such, the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, 95970 Electronic analysis of implanted neurostimulator pulse generator/transmitter without programming. This code reports testing without programming of the device and is included in implantation of the neurostimulator electrode(s) and pulse generator. Therefore, do not report 95970 with 43647, 43648, 43881, 43882, 61850-61888, 63650, 63655, 63661-63664, 63585, 63688, 64553, 64555, 64561, 64566, 64568-64570, 64575, 64580, 64581, 64585, 64590, or 64595 during the same operative session. Requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT Assistant October 2012 page 15, CPT guidelines stipulate that one must actually make a change to more than three parameters—not merely consider a change—to count toward the reporting of a complex code (ie, 95972). More than three parameters (rate, pulse amplitude, pulse duration, pulse frequency, eight or more electrode contacts, cycling, stimulation train duration, train spacing, number of programs, number of channels, alternating electrode polarities, dose time [stimulation parameters changing in time periods of minutes including dose lockout times]) must be changed in order to report complex reprogramming. In addition, assessing changes in more than one clinical feature (eg, rigidity, dyskinesia, tremor) also counts as one parameter for these purposes. As such, the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 M. Central Nervous System Assessments/Tests, Central nervous system (CNS) assessment/test CPT codes (e.g., 96130-96133, 96136-96146, 96105, 96125, 96127) shall not be reported for tests that are reportable as part of an E&M service when performed. In order to report a CNS assessment/ test CPT code, the test cannot be self-administered. It must be administered as required by the code descriptor of the reported CPT code. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 M. Central Nervous System Assessments/Tests, since the procedures described by CPT codes 96130-96139 are timed procedures, physicians shall not report time for duplicating information (collection or interpretation) included in the psychiatric diagnostic interview examination and/or psychological/neuropsychological evaluation services or test administration and scoring. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} Psychological or neuropsychological test administration and scoring by health care professional, two or more tests, any method; first 30 minutes is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, CPT code {ServiceCode} describes an "initial" service code. For a patient encounter, only one "initial" service code may be reported unless it is clinically indicated that, in the context for which it is intended, the drug or substance administrations occur at separate intravenous access sites. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, if both lumina of a double lumen catheter are used for infusions of different substances or drugs, only one "initial" infusion CPT code may be reported. The double lumen catheter permits intravenous access through a single vascular site. Thus, it would not be correct to report two "initial" infusion CPT codes, one for each lumen of the catheter. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 N. Chemotherapy Administration, CPT code {ServiceCode} describes an "initial" service code. For a patient encounter, only one "initial" service code may be reported unless it is clinically indicated that, in the context for which it is intended, the drug or substance administrations occur at separate intravenous access sites. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, hydration concurrent with other drug administration services is not separately reportable. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, if the sole purpose of fluid administration (e.g., saline, D5W, etc.) is to maintain patency of an access device, the infusion is neither diagnostic nor therapeutic and shall not be reported separately. Similarly, the fluid used to administer drugs/substances is incidental hydration and shall not be reported separately. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 N. Chemotherapy Administration, hydration concurrent with other drug administration services is not separately reportable. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, under the Outpatient Prospective Payment System (OPPS), drug administration services related to operative procedures are included in the associated procedural CPT codes. Examples of such drug administration services include, but are not limited to, anesthesia (local or other), hydration, and medications such as anxiolytics or antibiotics. Providers shall not report CPT codes 96360-96377 for these services. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, CPT code {ServiceCode} is reportable by physicians for services performed in physicians' offices. Drug administration services shall not be reported by physicians for services provided in a facility setting such as a hospital outpatient department or emergency department. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, drug administration services performed in an Ambulatory Surgical Center (ASC) related to a Medicare-approved ASC payable procedure are not separately reportable by physicians. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 N. Chemotherapy Administration, CPT code {ServiceCode} is reportable by physicians for services performed in physicians' offices. Drug administration services shall not be reported by physicians for services provided in a facility setting such as a hospital outpatient department or emergency department. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 N. Chemotherapy Administration, drug administration services performed in an Ambulatory Surgical Center (ASC) related to a Medicare-approved ASC payable procedure are not separately reportable by physicians. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 N. Chemotherapy Administration, CPT code 96368 may be reported with a maximum of one unit of service per patient encounter regardless of the number of concurrently infused drugs or the length of time for the concurrent infusion(s). Therefore, the request for {Qty} units of {ServiceCode} is denied and one (1) unit is approved.

Per NCCI, all services necessary to complete a procedure based upon standard medical/surgical practice are included in the procedure. Many procedures that are typically necessary to complete a more comprehensive procedure have been assigned independent CPT codes because they may be performed independently in other settings. The service described by CPT code 96372 (Therapeutic, prophylactic, or diagnostic injection) is typically included when performing the procedure described by CPT code 55700 (Biopsy, prostate; needle or punch, single or multiple, any approach) and is therefore bundled into CPT code 55700. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, CPT codes 96521 and 96522 shall not be reported for accessing or flushing an indwelling peripherally-placed intravenous catheter port (external to skin), subcutaneous port, or non-programmable subcutaneous pump. Accessing and flushing these devices is an inherent service facilitating these infusion(s) and is not reported separately. Thus, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 N. Chemotherapy Administration, CPT codes 96521 and 96522 shall not be reported for accessing or flushing an indwelling peripherally-placed intravenous catheter port (external to skin), subcutaneous port, or non-programmable subcutaneous pump. Accessing and flushing these devices is an inherent service facilitating these infusion(s) and is not reported separately. Thus, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, CPT codes 96416 and 96425 include the initial filling and maintenance of a portable or implantable infusion pump. CPT codes 96521 and 96522 are used to report subsequent refilling of the pump and shall not be reported with CPT code 96416 or 96425. Thus, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 N. Chemotherapy Administration, CPT codes 96416 and 96425 include the initial filling and maintenance of a portable or implantable infusion pump. CPT codes 96521 and 96522 are used to report subsequent refilling of the pump and shall not be reported with CPT code 96416 or 96425. Thus, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, CPT code 96522 shall not be reported for accessing a non-programmable implantable intravenous device for the provision of infusion(s) or chemotherapy administration. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 B. Therapeutic or Diagnostic Infusions/Injections and Immunizations, flushing or irrigation of an implanted vascular access port or device of a drug delivery system prior to or subsequent to the administration of chemotherapeutic or non-chemotherapeutic drugs is integral to the drug administration service and is not separately reportable. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies of the NCCI Policy Manual, a component service integral to a comprehensive service is not separately reportable. Surgical closure and dressings are considered component services integral to a comprehensive service and therefore, not separately reportable. As such, the use of negative pressure wound therapy (e.g., vacuum assisted drainage collection) is not separately reportable when it is placed over a primarily closed wound site. In this case, it is being used as a component of the dressing and thus integral to the comprehensive service. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, code {ServiceCode} Moderate sedation services provided by the same physician or other qualified health care professional performing the diagnostic or therapeutic service that the sedation supports, requires the presence of an independent trained observer to monitor the patient's level of consciousness and physiological status. The clinical documentation provided does not sufficiently describe or support the requisite criteria for approval of the requested CPT code. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, code 99153 Moderate sedation services provided by the same physician or other qualified health care professional performing the diagnostic or therapeutic service that the sedation supports, each additional 15 minutes intraservice time; includes monitoring of the patient's response to drugs and vital signs. The clinical documentation submitted for review no intraoperative report detailing vital signs, intraoperative levels of consciousness/sedation, nor time as required. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 8, CPT code 64561 (Percutaneous implantation of neurostimulator electrode array; sacral nerve...) is priced to include a "percutaneous neuro test stimulation kit." This kit includes a "test stimulation lead." HCPCS code A4290 (Sacral nerve stimulation test lead, each) shall not be reported with CPT code 64561. As such, HCPCS code A4290 is denied as inclusive to 64561.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, if a definitive surgical procedure requires access through diseased tissue (e.g., necrotic skin, abscess, hematoma, seroma), a separate service for this access (e.g., debridement, incision and drainage) is not separately reportable. As such, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

The request for code/service CPT {ServiceCode} must be listed separately in addition to the code for the primary procedure.  Thus, it requires an approved primary ("parent") procedure code.  Since no primary ("parent") is approved, CPT {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, physicians must report services correctly. Procedures shall be reported with the most comprehensive CPT code that describes the services performed. A CPT code shall be reported only if all services described by the code are performed. As such, the requested service code {ServiceCode} is denied and CPT code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a CPT code may be reported only if all services described by that code have been performed. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 1 G. Anesthesia Service Included in the Surgical Procedure, CPT codes describing anesthesia services or services that are bundled into anesthesia shall not be reported in addition to the surgical or medical procedure requiring the anesthesia services if performed by the same physician. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Anesthesia, with limited exceptions Medicare Anesthesia Rules prevent separate payment for anesthesia for a medical or surgical procedure when provided by the physician performing the procedure. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, the clinical documentation provided in the narrative operative report does not sufficiently describe or support the requisite criteria for approval of the requested CPT code. The operative report submitted for review appears to document that the angioplasty balloon was used as a mechanical thrombectomy device. Percutaneous transluminal mechanical thrombectomy is approved elsewhere in the claim. Thus, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."
The submitted documentation meets the requirements for approval.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Arthroscopy, with the exception of the knee and shoulder, arthroscopic debridement shall not be reported separately with a surgical arthroscopy when performed on the same joint at the same patient encounter. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Arthroscopy, If an arthroscopic procedure is converted to an open procedure, only the open procedure may be reported. Neither a surgical arthroscopy nor a diagnostic arthroscopy code shall be reported with the open procedure code when a surgical arthroscopic procedure is converted to an open procedure. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per AMA Principles of CPT Coding 9th edition 2017, the stent placement codes (36903, 36906) include balloon angioplasty, therefore, balloon angioplasty is not reported separately, even if it is performed on a separate lesion in the same dialysis segment. Thus, requested balloon angioplasty code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the stent placement code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT Assistant September 2012, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied, as there is no CPT code for reporting an arthroscopic biceps tenotomy. CPT Assistant states this procedure is considered a debridement procedure. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and CPT code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a physician shall not unbundle a bilateral procedure code into two unilateral procedure codes. As such, the requested service code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 5 C. Respiratory System, a biopsy performed in conjunction with a more extensive nasal/sinus procedure is not separately reportable unless the biopsy is examined pathologically prior to the more extensive procedure and the decision to proceed with the more extensive procedure is based on the result of the pathologic examination. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a biopsy is not separately reportable if used for the purpose of assessing margins of resection or verifying resectability. If a biopsy is performed and submitted for pathologic evaluation that will be completed after the more extensive procedure is performed, the biopsy is not separately reportable with the more extensive procedure. Therefore, requested biopsy, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, NCCI and Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons September 2018, intraoperative placement of clips or markers at the time of open excision of a breast lesion (19125–19126) or at the time of a mastectomy procedure (19301–19307) is inherent to the procedure and not separately reportable. BioZorb is an FDA-approved 3D implantable marker that consists of a spiral, bioabsorbable framework embedded with 6 permanent, titanium clips designed to precisely mark a surgical excision site. If the BioZorb device is placed to mark the surgical site for later identification, no additional code should be reported. Thus, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons September 2018, intraoperative placement of clips or markers at the time of open excision of a breast lesion (19125–19126) or at the time of a mastectomy procedure (19301–19307) is inherent to the procedure and not separately reportable. BioZorb is an FDA-approved 3D implantable marker that consists of a spiral, bioabsorbable framework embedded with titanium clips designed to precisely mark a surgical excision site. It is not a breast prosthesis used for reconstruction. As such, the request for breast prosthesis code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented".

Per CPT Assistant May 2012, the harvest of bone marrow aspirate for platelet-rich plasma (PRP) containing stem cells is considered inclusive to Platelet-rich Plasma (0232T). Per CMS Payment Policy, use of Platelet Rich Plasma is only reportable as an aid to help heal ulcers. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant May 2012, the harvest of bone marrow aspirate for platelet-rich plasma (PRP) containing stem cells is considered inclusive to Platelet-rich Plasma (0232T). Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Bone Anchored Implants for Osseointegrated Hearing Appliances
Rationale.RationaleText: Per CPT Assistant January 2019 page 14, Report code 69799, Unlisted procedure, middle ear for a bone-conduction hearing system whereby sound vibrations are transferred by magnetic coupling from the external processor to the bone implant to the cochlea (inner ear). The work of placing an osseointegrated bone-conduction hearing system that uses magnetic connection and coupling is substantially different from the work of placing a percutaneous system. Although the service performed by the surgeon involves the placement of a screw into the skull, it does not involve the creation of a percutaneous channel through which the screw protrudes and to which the processor is attached. When reporting an unlisted code to describe a procedure or service, it may be necessary to submit supporting documentation (eg, procedure report) with the claim to provide adequate description of the nature, extent, and need for the procedure; and the time, effort, and equipment necessary to provide the service. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Carpal Tunnel Surgery & Distal Radius Fracture
Rationale.RationaleText: Per AAOS Code-X 2020, the request for carpal tunnel release, as described in the operative report submitted for review, is considered inclusive to the primary fracture repair code, as there is no pre-existing compression neuropathy of the median nerve documented prior to the fracture. As such, the carpal tunnel release and neuroplasty of the median nerve is considered included in the primary fracture repair. Thus, in this clinical situation, {ServiceCode} is included in {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4, "casting/splinting/strapping shall not be reported separately if a restorative treatment or procedure to stabilize or protect a fracture, injury, or dislocation and/or afford comfort to the patient is also performed." Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, 35371 thromboendarterectomy includes patch graft, if performed; common femoral. Unless the procedure involves a significant length of the deep or superficial femoral artery, or external iliac artery, report only the common femoral procedure (35371). The operative report submitted for review describes a common femoral endarterectomy. As such, the requested service code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per American Society of Plastic Surgeons CPT Corner Plastic Surgery News, October/November 2019, a chimeric Flap is defined as a free muscle, myocutaneous or fasciocutaneous flap that has been harvested with an additional separately identifiable soft tissue component perfused by the same origin pedicle. When coding, the highest-value free flap is coded first as the primary procedure. Additional codes are coded in the 15734-15738 code series, along with a reduced service modifier 52. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

As per the Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons April 2017, when a laparoscopic port is placed through an umbilical or incisional hernia during the performance of a laparoscopic cholecystectomy, with subsequent closure of the hernia port site, only the laparoscopic cholecystectomy is reported. When both procedures are performed through the same incision, the hernia repair is considered inclusive to the cholecystectomy, and is not separately reportable. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 6 H. General Policy Statements, if an excised section of intestine includes a fistula tract, a fistula closure code shall not be reported separately. Closure of the fistula is included in the excision of intestine. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 6 H. General Policy Statements, if closure of an enterostomy or fistula involving the intestine requires resection and anastomosis of a segment of intestine, the resection and anastomosis of the intestine are not separately reportable. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, since a colectomy requires exposure of the colon, the laparotomy and adhesiolysis to expose the colon are not separately reportable. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, the global surgical package for an operative procedure includes all intra-operative services that are normally a usual and necessary part of the procedure. Additionally the global surgical package includes all medical and surgical services required of the surgeon during the postoperative period of the surgery to treat complications that do not require return to the operating room. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per American Society of Plastic Surgeons CPT Corner Plastic Surgery News October/November 2018, component separation involves incision of the external oblique muscles and their elevation off the internal oblique muscles, to the anterior axillary lines. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} excisional preparation is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Introduction, "The edits and policies do not include all possible combinations of correct coding edits or types of unbundling that exist. Providers are obligated to code correctly even if edits do not exist to prevent use of an inappropriate code combination." In addition, per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I, "A physician shall not unbundle services that are integral to a more comprehensive procedure." Therefore, in this clinical situation, the service described by CPT {ServiceCode} is integral to the comprehensive service, CPT code {IncludedCode}. As such, the request for component service, CPT code {ServiceCode}, is denied as inclusive to comprehensive service, CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 6 C. Endoscopic Services, control of bleeding is an integral component of endoscopic procedures and is not separately reportable. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, is included in the global surgery package (GSP) for the primary procedure and cannot be reported separately. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 Surgery Integumentary System, If lesion removal, incision, or repair requires debridement of non-viable tissue surrounding a lesion, incision, or injury in order to complete the procedure, the debridement is not separately reportable. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} debridement and/or surgical preparation is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4, Subsection I. General Policy Statements Debridement of tissue in the surgical field of another musculoskeletal procedure is not separately reportable. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4, Subsection I. General Policy Statements, debridement of tissue in the surgical field of another musculoskeletal procedure is not separately reportable. For example, debridement of muscle and/or bone associated with excision of a tumor of bone is not separately reportable. Similarly, debridement of tissue superficial to, but in the surgical field of a musculoskeletal procedure, is not separately reportable. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4, Subsection I. General Policy Statements, debridement of tissue in the surgical field of another musculoskeletal procedure is not separately reportable. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual, Chapter 4, Section H (General Policy Statement #11): Debridement of tissue in the surgical field of another musculoskeletal procedure is not separately reportable. Similarly, debridement of tissue (e.g., CPT codes 11042, 11045, 11720-11721, 97597, 97598) superficial to, but in the surgical field, of a musculoskeletal procedure is not separately reportable. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3 E. Lesion Removal, if lesion removal, incision, or repair requires debridement of non-viable tissue surrounding a lesion, incision, or injury in order to complete the procedure, the debridement is not separately reportable. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.
Per CPT, the requested CPT code, {ServiceCode}, was deleted, effective January 1, 2020 and therefore, is denied as "Not Documented."
Per CPT, the requested CPT code, {ServiceCode}, was deleted, effective January 1, 2021 and therefore, is denied as "Not Documented."

As per Chapter 1, General Correct Coding Policies, NCCI Policy Manual, Physicians must report services correctly. Procedures should be reported with the most comprehensive CPT code that describes the services performed. As such, the requested service, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and CPT code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

As per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 5, open and percutaneous interventional vascular procedures include operative angiograms and/or venograms. Therefore, diagnostic angiograms/venograms shall not be reported separately. There is insufficient documentation in the operative report to approve the modifier requested. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

The requested service code, {ServiceCode}, has already been reviewed on another service line in this claim. No additional documentation is been provided to indicated that this service has been performed again. As such, this request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is considered a "Duplicate" and is denied as "Not Documented."

As per the Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons April 2017, elevation of subcutaneous flaps is inherent to the incisional/ventral hernia repair codes and is not separately reportable as tissue rearrangements. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per AMA Principles of CPT Coding, report only one (1) embolization code for a single operative field, regardless of the number of vessels or embolic agents required to complete the embolization. Therefore, the request for {Qty} units of service for embolization code {ServiceCode} is denied and one (1) unit of service is approved.

Per AMA Principles of CPT Coding, report only one (1) embolization code for a single operative field, regardless of the number of vessels or numbers of embolic agents required to complete the embolization. An embolization code has been approved elsewhere on the claim. Therefore, the request for embolization code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy, if a bypass graft procedure requires an endarterectomy to insert the graft, only the code describing the bypass may be reported. The endarterectomy is not separately reportable since it is a component service. Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, while it is not possible to discuss all NCCI PTP edits based upon the principle of the standards of medical/surgical practice due to space limitations, there are several general principles that can be applied. A component service necessary to complete a comprehensive service, is an accepted standard of care when performing the comprehensive service, and is not a separately distinguishable procedure when performed with the comprehensive service. As such, the request for component service, CPT code {ServiceCode}, is denied as inclusive to comprehensive service, CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Endoscopic Endonasal Skull Base/Deny and Suggest
Rationale.RationaleText: Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a physician shall not report a CPT code for a specific procedure if it does not accurately describe the service performed. It is inappropriate to report the best fit CPT code unless it accurately describes the service performed, and all components of the CPT code were performed. Presently, there are no existing CPT codes that accurately describe endoscopic endonasal surgery for removal of a skull base tumor. The endoscopic endonasal pituitary tumor removal code (62165) is intended only for resection of pituitary tumors via this approach. If a physician provides a service that is not accurately described by other CPT codes, the service shall be reported using an unlisted procedure code. Therefore, an unlisted code must be reported for the endoscopic endonasal approach for removal of non-pituitary neoplastic, vascular or infectious lesions at the base of the skull. Thus, the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and unlisted procedure code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a physician shall not report a CPT code for a specific procedure if it does not accurately describe the service performed. It is inappropriate to report the best fit CPT code unless it accurately describes the service performed, and all components of the CPT code were performed. Presently, there are no existing CPT codes that accurately describe endoscopic endonasal surgery for removal of a skull base tumor. The endoscopic endonasal pituitary tumor removal code (62165) is intended only for resection of pituitary tumors via this approach. If a physician provides a service that is not accurately described by other CPT codes, the service shall be reported using an unlisted procedure code. Therefore, an unlisted code must be reported for the endoscopic endonasal approach for removal of non-pituitary neoplastic, vascular or infectious lesions at the base of the skull. Thus, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per American Academy of Otolaryngology-Head and Neck Surgery 2020 Policy, for endoscopic medial maxillectomy, report Unlisted Procedure Code 31299 with appropriate comparator codes and special report as described in AMA CPT Surgery Guidelines; or consider 31256 Nasal/sinus endoscopy, surgical, with maxillary antrostomy; or 31267 Maxillary antrostomy with removal of tissue from maxillary sinus appended with modifier -22 in conjunction with 30130 Excision inferior turbinate, partial or complete, any method. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, if an endoscopic procedure is performed at the same patient encounter as a non-endoscopic procedure to ensure no intraoperative injury occurred or verify the procedure was performed correctly, the endoscopic procedure is not separately reportable with the non-endoscopic procedure. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, if an endoscopic procedure is performed at the same patient encounter as a non-endoscopic procedure to ensure no intraoperative injury occurred or verify the procedure was performed correctly, the endoscopic procedure is not separately reportable with the non-endoscopic procedure. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per American Academy Otolaryngology-Head and Neck Surgery 2020 Policy, report codes 31295-31298 Nasal/sinus endoscopy, surgical, with dilation (eg, balloon dilation) when tissue is displaced. Small amounts of bone removed to allow "access" do not allow the use of formal Endoscopic Sinus Surgery (ESS) codes (31253-31288). Thus, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 6 C. Endoscopic Services, if an endoscopic procedure fails and is converted into an open procedure at the same patient encounter, only the open procedure is reportable. Neither a surgical endoscopy nor diagnostic endoscopy procedure code shall be reported with the open procedure code when an endoscopic procedure is converted to an open procedure. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 6 C. Endoscopic Services, if an endoscopy or enteroscopy is performed as a common standard of practice when performing another service, the endoscopy or enteroscopy is not separately reportable. For example, if a small intestinal endoscopy or enteroscopy is performed during the creation or revision of an enterostomy, the small intestinal endoscopy or enteroscopy is not separately reportable. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, Endovenous ablation therapy of incompetent vein is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, exposure and exploration of the surgical field is integral to an operative procedure and is not separately reportable. If exploration of the surgical field results in additional procedures other than the primary procedure, the additional procedures may generally be reported separately. However, a procedure designated by the CPT code descriptor as a "separate procedure" is not separately reportable if performed in a region anatomically related to the other procedure(s) through the same skin incision, orifice, or surgical approach. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4, if closure of a fistula requires excision of a portion of an organ into which the fistula passes, excision of that tissue shall not be reported separately. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Fractures, when a fracture or dislocation is repaired, only one fracture/dislocation repair code may be reported. Closed repair codes, percutaneous repair codes, and open repair codes for the same anatomic site are mutually exclusive of one another, and only one of these codes may be reported for the repair of a fracture or dislocation at an anatomic site. Thus, in this clinical situation, {ServiceCode} is included in {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual, Chapter 5, during a cardiac catheterization procedure the physicians often injects dye to examine the renal arteries and/or iliac arteries. These services may be reported with HCPCS code G0278. A physician shall not report CPT codes 75625 (Abdominal aortography) or 75630 (Abdominal aortography with bilateral iliofemoral lower extremity angiography) unless a complete study including venous phase is performed and interpreted. There is insufficient documentation in the operative report to approve the modifier requested. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.
Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Arthroscopy, chondroplasty in any compartment is included in the primary procedure. Thus, G0289 is included in {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, the performance of certain procedures may require significantly different approaches when performed in a male as opposed to a female. Some CPT code descriptors designate these procedures by specifying if the service or procedure is to be reported for a male or a female or by anatomical description. CPT code combinations that are identical, except that one code describes a procedure for a female and the other describes a procedure for a male, cannot be reported for the same beneficiary by the same provider at the same session. CPT code {IncludedCode} and CPT code {ServiceCode} represent such a combination and should not be reported together.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Arthroscopy, HCPCS code G0289 (Arthroscopy, knee, surgical; for removal of loose body, foreign body, debridement/shaving of articular cartilage at the time of other surgical knee arthroscopy in a different compartment of the same knee) may be reported with other knee arthroscopy codes. The operative report submitted for review does not document that this work was performed in a different compartment of the same knee. Reference is NCCI Policy, Chapter IV, Arthroscopy. Therefore, HCPCS code G0289 is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

All grafts which are processed or "off the shelf" (such as amniotic stem cell grafts), are included in the global service package for the primary procedure and are not separately reported. Reference is CPT Assistant, December 2013.. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

The CPT code descriptor for some genitourinary procedures includes a hernia repair. A HCPCS/CPT code for a hernia repair is not separately reportable unless the hernia repair is performed at a different site through a separate incision. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3, CPT codes for incision and drainage shall not be reported separately with other procedures such as excision, repair, destruction, removal, etc., when performed at the same anatomic site at the same patient encounter. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3, If it is necessary to incise and/or drain a lesion as part of another procedure or in order to gain access to an area for another procedure, the incision and/or drainage is not separately reportable if performed at the same patient encounter. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 3, incision and drainage services, as related to the integumentary system, generally involve cutaneous or subcutaneous drainage of cysts, pustules, infections, hematomas, abscesses, seromas or fluid collections. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented".

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 6 E. Abdominal Procedures, if an iatrogenic laceration/perforation of the small or large intestine occurs during the course of another procedure, repair of the laceration/perforation is not separately reportable. Treatment of an iatrogenic complication of surgery such as an intestinal laceration/perforation is not a separately reportable service. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a component service integral to a comprehensive service is not separately reportable. Imaging/ultrasound guidance are considered component services integral to a comprehensive service and therefore, not separately reportable. As such, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.
Review of the Current Procedural Terminology (CPT) Coding Index, reveals that requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is not an active CPT code at this time and is therefore denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 1, Paragraph V. Medically Unlikely Edits (MUEs), a MUE for a HCPCS/CPT code is the maximum number of units of service (UOS) under most circumstances allowable by the same provider for the same beneficiary on the same date of service. The requested CPT code/service cannot be approved because it exceeds the Medically Unlikely Edit (MUE) for the procedure. Thus, the requested CPT code, {ServiceCode} is thus denied as "Not Documented."

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Incorrect DOS, Patient or Provider OP Report
Rationale.RationaleText: The narrative operative report included with the clinical documentation is for a different date of service (DOS), patient or provider than the claim submitted for review. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Rationale.RationaleText: As per Chapter 1, General Correct Coding Policies, NCCI Policy Manual, Physicians must report services correctly. Procedures should be reported with the most comprehensive CPT code that describes the services performed. A more accurate or precise CPT code should be used to report this service. As such, the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is not supported by the clinical documentation in the operative report submitted for review and is denied as "Not Documented."

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Incorrect Number of Units of Service Requested
Rationale.RationaleText: Per CPT, the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} meets the requirements for approval. However; based on the clinical documentation submitted for review, it appears that the request is for an incorrect number of units of service (UOS). Therefore, the request for {Qty} units of service for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and {ApprovedUnits} units of service are approved.

The requested CPT code, {ServiceCode}, meets the requirements for approval. However; based on the clinical documentation submitted for review, it appears that the request is for an incorrect number of units. Therefore, the request for {Qty} units of {ServiceCode} is denied and {ApprovedUnits} units is approved.

Per CPT, codes 35301-35372, (thromboendarterectomy, including patch graft) include establishing both inflow and outflow by any method. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the thromboendarterectomy code {IncludedCode} as a component service. Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, while it is not possible to discuss all NCCI PTP edits based upon the principle of the standards of medical/surgical practice due to space limitations, there are several general principles that can be applied. A component service necessary to complete a comprehensive service, is an accepted standard of care when performing the comprehensive service, and is not a separately distinguishable procedure when performed with the comprehensive service. As such, the request for component service, CPT code {ServiceCode}, is denied as inclusive to comprehensive service, CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Anesthesia, injections of local anesthesia for musculoskeletal procedures (surgical or manipulative) are not separately reportable. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a component service integral to a comprehensive service is not separately reportable. Insertion of intravenous access for medication administration is considered a component service integral to a comprehensive service and is therefore, not separately reportable. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 5 D. Cardiovascular System, cardiopulmonary bypass requires insertion of cannulas into the venous and arterial circulation, which is integral to the procedure. HCPCS codes for insertion of the cannulas into the venous and arterial circulation shall not be reported separately. Therefore, HCPCS code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, the clinical documentation provided in the narrative operative report does not sufficiently describe or support the requisite criteria for approval of the requested CPT code. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, HCPCS code L8680 Implantable neurostimulator electrode, each is considered inclusive to 63650 implantation of neurostimulator electrode array, epidural or 63655 implantation of neurostimulator electrodes, plate/paddle, epidural. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 6 F. Laparoscopy, if a laparoscopic procedure is converted to an open procedure, only the open procedure may be reported. Neither a surgical laparoscopy nor a diagnostic laparoscopy code shall be reported with the open procedure code when a laparoscopic procedure is converted to an open procedure. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Levator Muscle transposition during cleft Palate repair (42200)
Rationale.RationaleText: Per American Society of Plastic Surgeons 2020 Coding Workshop Workbook, Transposition and suturing of the levator muscles is inclusive in the cleft palate repair code 42200. Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, the operative report submitted for review, does not describe the requisite level of anatomic detail of the extent of the regional lymphatic nodal dissection, and/or the number of nodes excised, all necessary criteria according to the guidelines, for the CPT code requested. As such, {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

NCCI considers a middle turbinate reduction as an access route to the sinuses. The middle turbinate was hypertrophic and was reduced. Concha Bullosae are not documented. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, when the work required to provide a service is substantially greater than typically required, it may be identified by adding modifier 22 to the usual procedure code. Documentation must support the substantial additional work and the reason for the additional work (i.e., increased intensity, time, technical difficulty of procedure, and severity of patient's condition, physical and mental effort required). The clinical documentation submitted for review does not support the substantial additional work and the reason for the additional work. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode}-22 is denied and {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per AAOS Now June 2008, obesity in itself does not allow for use of Modifier 22. Appropriate use of Modifier 22 requires documentation of a substantial increase of time and effort required to perform the procedure. Since this was not documented in the operative report submitted for review, the request for Modifier 22 cannot be approved. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode}-22 is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CMS Physician Fee Schedule Medicare Rules, Diagnostic tests with a PC/TC Indicator of 1 identify codes that have both a professional and technical component. Modifiers 26 and TC can be used with these codes. The total RVUs for codes reported with modifier 26 include values for physician work, practice expense, and malpractice expense. The total RVUs for codes reported with modifier TC include values for practice expense and malpractice expense only. The total RVUs for codes reported without a modifier include values for physician work, practice expense, and malpractice expense. As such, there is no difference, in terms of reimbursement, whether the code is reported with or without modifier 26. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CMS, practitioners and outpatient hospitals are required to report bilateral surgical procedures with modifier 50 and one (1) unit of service on a single claim line unless the code descriptor defines the procedure as "bilateral". If the code descriptor defines the procedure as a "bilateral" procedure, it shall be reported with one unit of service without modifier 50. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT, under certain circumstances a service or procedure is partially reduced or eliminated at the discretion of the physician. Under these circumstances the service provided can be identified by its usual CPT code and the addition of modifier 52, signifying that the service is reduced. This provides a means of reporting reduced services without disturbing the identification of the basic service. Review of the operative/procedure report suggests that a reduced level of service was provided in this case. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT, under certain circumstances, the physician or other qualified health care professional may elect to terminate a surgical or diagnostic procedure. Due to extenuating circumstances or those that threaten the well being of the patient, it may be necessary to indicate that a surgical or diagnostic procedure was started but discontinued. This circumstance may be reported by adding modifier 53 to the code reported by the individual for the discontinued procedure. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT and NCCI Chapter 1 - Distinct Procedural Service: Under certain circumstances, it may be necessary to indicate that a procedure or service was distinct or independent from other non-E/M services performed on the same day. Modifier 59 is used to identify procedures/services, other than E/M services, that are not normally reported together, but are appropriate under the circumstances. Documentation must support a different session, different procedure or surgery, different site or organ system, separate incision/excision, separate lesion, or separate injury (or area of injury in extensive injuries) not ordinarily encountered or performed on the same day by the same individual. Thus the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 1, Modifier 59 or XS is used appropriately for different anatomic sites during the same encounter only when procedures which are not ordinarily performed or encountered on the same day are performed on different organs, or different anatomic regions, or in limited situations on different, non-contiguous lesions in different anatomic regions of the same organ. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CMS guidelines, reimbursement for Assistant Surgeon services, as indicated by modifiers 80, 81, 82, or AS is not allowed for procedures where reimbursement has been provided for eligible Co-Surgeon services, using the same surgical procedure code, during the same encounter. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as not eligible for assistant surgeon reimbursement.

When two surgeons work together as primary surgeons performing distinct parts of a procedure, each surgeon should report his/her distinct operative work by adding modifier 62 to the procedure code and any associated add-on codes for that procedure as long as both surgeons continue to work together as primary surgeons. Documentation must be submitted that clearly documents the work of each surgeon. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

According to the CMS National Physician Fee Schedule (NPFS), only physicians serving as Assistants-at-Surgery should report the same procedure code(s) as the primary surgeon appended with one of the following modifiers 80, 81 or 82. Modifier AS must be appended to the claim line when reporting assistant surgery performed by a physician assistant (PA) or certified registered nurse practitioner (CRNP). As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

As per the CMS National Physician Fee Schedule (NPFS), the requested service code {ServiceCode} has a payment policy indicator of 0. As such, payment restriction for assistants at surgery applies to this procedure unless supporting documentation is submitted to establish medical necessity. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as not eligible for assistant surgeon reimbursement.

As per the CMS National Physician Fee Schedule (NPFS), the requested service code has a payment policy indicator of 1. As such, statutory payment restriction for assistants at surgery applies to this procedure. Assistant at Surgery may not be paid. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as not eligible for assistant surgeon reimbursement.

As per the CMS National Physician Fee Schedule (NPFS), the requested service code has a payment policy indicator of 9. As such, Assistant at surgery concept does not apply. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as not eligible for assistant surgeon reimbursement.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Medically Unlikely Edits (MUEs), procedures performed on fingers should be reported with modifiers FA, F1-F9, and, performed on toes should be reported with modifiers TA, T1-T9. The MUE values for many finger and toe procedures are one, based on use of these modifiers for clinical scenarios in which the same procedure is performed on more than one finger or toe. The required modifier has not been appended as required by NCCI coding policy. Thus, the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Medically Unlikely Edits (MUEs), procedures performed on fingers should be reported with modifiers FA, F1-F9. The MUE values for many finger procedures is one, based on use of these modifiers for clinical scenarios in which the same procedure is performed on more than one finger. The required modifier has not been appended as required by NCCI coding policy. Thus the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Medically Unlikely Edits (MUEs), procedures performed on fingers should be reported with modifiers FA, F1-F9, and, performed on toes should be reported with modifiers TA, T1-T9. The MUE values for many finger and toe procedures are one, based on use of these modifiers for clinical scenarios in which the same procedure is performed on more than one finger or toe. The required modifier has not been appended as required by NCCI coding policy. Thus the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Rationale.RationaleSummary: NOT For X - Most Comprehensive CPT Code (NCCI)
Rationale.RationaleText: Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, physicians must report services correctly. Procedures shall be reported with the most comprehensive CPT code that describes the services performed. A CPT code shall be reported only if all services described by the code are performed. As such, the requested service code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 Fractures, Dislocations and Casting/Splinting/Strapping, when it is necessary to perform skeletal/joint manipulation under anesthesia to assess range of motion, reduce a fracture or for any other purpose during another procedure in an anatomically related area, the corresponding manipulation code (e.g., CPT codes 22505, 23700, 27275, 27570, 27860) is not separately reportable. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, procedures shall be reported with the most comprehensive CPT code that describes the services performed. Physicians must not unbundle the services described by a CPT code. A physician shall not fragment a procedure into component parts and report multiple CPT codes when a single comprehensive CPT code describes these services. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

As per the Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons April 2017, multiple hernias (often described as "swiss-cheese hernias") repaired during the same operative session through the SAME laparoscopic trocar sites, or through the SAME open laparotomy incision; and repaired with a single prosthetic sheet of mesh, when used, are considered inherently inclusive and cannot be reported separately. Additionally, multiple hernia defects of the abdominal wall, in proximity, count as a single hernia. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

The requested CPT code is an NCCI Procedure to Procedure (PTP) edit with another CPT code based on the PTP rationale of "CPT 'Separate procedure' definition." Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, "If a CPT code descriptor includes the term "separate procedure," the CPT code may not be reported separately with a related procedure. The CMS interprets this designation to prohibit the separate reporting of a "separate procedure" when performed with another procedure in an anatomically related region often through the same skin incision, orifice, or surgical approach." The proper criteria for approval of a Modifier to bypass the NCCI PTP edit has not been met. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: NCCI CPT Manual or CMS manual coding instruction:
Rationale.RationaleText: The requested CPT code is an NCCI Procedure to Procedure (PTP) edit with another CPT code based on the PTP rationale of "CPT Manual or CMS manual coding instructions." CMS often publishes coding instructions in its rules, manuals, and notices. The "CPT Manual" also includes coding instructions which may be found in the "Introduction," individual chapters, and appendices. In individual chapters, the instructions may appear at the beginning of a chapter, at the beginning of a subsection of the chapter, or after specific CPT codes. Physicians should follow "CPT Manual" instructions unless the CMS has provided different coding or reporting instructions. The proper criteria for approval of a Modifier to bypass the NCCI PTP edit has not been met. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

The requested CPT code is an NCCI Procedure to Procedure (PTP) edit with another CPT code based on the PTP rationale of "HCPCS/CPT procedure code definition." Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, "the HCPCS/CPT code descriptors of 2 codes are often the basis of an NCCI PTP edit. If 2 HCPCS/CPT codes describe redundant services, they shall not be reported separately." The proper criteria for approval of a Modifier to bypass the NCCI PTP edit has not been met. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: NCCI Misuse of column two code with column one code:
Rationale.RationaleText: The requested CPT code is an NCCI Procedure to Procedure (PTP) edit with another CPT code based on the PTP rationale of "Misuse of column two code with column one code." Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, "The CMS manuals and instructions often describe groups of HCPCS/CPT codes that should not be reported together for the Medicare program. Edits based on these instructions are often included as misuse of a Column Two code with a Column One code. A HCPCS/CPT code descriptor does not include exhaustive information about the code. Physicians who are not familiar with a HCPCS/CPT code may incorrectly report the code in a context different than intended. The NCCI program has identified HCPCS/CPT codes that are incorrectly reported with other HCPCS/CPT codes as a result of the misuse of the Column Two code with the Column One code." The proper criteria for approval of a Modifier to bypass the NCCI PTP edit has not been met. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

The requested CPT code is an NCCI Procedure to Procedure (PTP) edit with another CPT code. Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, the "CPT Manual" often describes groups of similar codes differing in the complexity of the service. NCCI designates two procedures as PTP edited pairs when the less complex service is included in the more complex service and is not separately reportable. The proper criteria for approval of a Modifier to bypass the NCCI PTP edit has not been met. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

The requested CPT code is an NCCI Procedure to Procedure (PTP) edit with another CPT code based on the PTP rationale of "Mutually exclusive procedures." Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, "Many procedure codes cannot be reported together because they are mutually exclusive of each other. Mutually exclusive procedures cannot reasonably be performed at the same anatomic site or same patient encounter." The proper criteria for approval of a Modifier to bypass the NCCI PTP edit has not been met. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

The requested CPT code is an NCCI Procedure to Procedure (PTP) edit with another CPT code based on the PTP rationale of "Sequential procedure." Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, "some surgical procedures may be performed by different surgical approaches. If an initial surgical approach to a procedure fails and a second surgical approach is used at the same patient encounter, only the HCPCS/CPT code corresponding to the second surgical approach may be reported." The proper criteria for approval of a Modifier to bypass the NCCI PTP edit has not been met. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

The requested CPT code is an NCCI Procedure to Procedure (PTP) edit with another CPT code based on the PTP rationale of "Standards of medical/surgical practice." Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, many NCCI PTP edits are based upon the standards of medical/surgical practice. Services that are integral to another service are component parts of the more comprehensive service. Services integral to HCPCS/CPT code defined procedures are included in those procedures based upon the standards of medical/surgical practice. It is inappropriate to separately report services that are integral to another procedure with that procedure. The proper criteria for approval of a Modifier to bypass the NCCI PTP edit has not been met. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT Assistant October 2018 and January 2014, the Subchondroplasty (SCP) procedure is a minimally invasive repair designed to treat subchondral bone defects associated with chronic bone marrow lesions by filling the defect with a bone-substitute material. There is no specific CPT code that accurately describes the injection of calcium phosphate into a femur fracture. Therefore, an Unlisted procedure code should be reported when SCP is performed for a femur fracture. When reporting an unlisted code to describe a procedure or service, it is be necessary to submit supporting documentation (eg, procedure report) along with the claim to provide an adequate description of the nature, extent, and need for the procedure; and the time, effort, and equipment necessary to provide the service. Either an incorrect CPT code was reported and/or the required special report was not provided with the clinical documentation submitted for review. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per AMA Principles of CPT Coding, the entire femoral/popliteal territory in a lower extremity is considered a single vessel for CPT reporting, specifically for endovascular lower extremity revascularization. In addition, the tibioperoneal trunk is considered part of the tibial/peroneal territory, and is not considered a fourth segment of vessel in the tibio-peroneal family for CPT reporting of endovascular lower extremity interventions. In the clinical documents submitted for review, the vessels treated/imaged, as described, comprise a single vascular family and no additional vessels were treated/imaged. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."
The requested CPT code, {ServiceCode}, is considered "Out-of-Scope" and not reviewable per contract.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 I. Cardiovascular Services, there are 5 major coronary arteries (left main, left anterior descending, left circumflex, right, and ramus intermedius). Only one PCI code may be reported for all percutaneous coronary artery interventions (PCIs) of a major coronary artery through the native circulation. However, PCI treatment of a different second segment of a major coronary artery through a bypass graft may also be reported with a different PCI code for revascularization treatment through a coronary artery bypass. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Cardiovascular Services, a cardiac catheterization procedure or a percutaneous coronary artery interventional procedure may require ECG tracings to assess chest pain during the procedure. These ECG tracings are not separately reportable. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 11 I. Cardiovascular Services, percutaneous coronary artery interventions (PCI) include stent placement, atherectomy, and balloon angioplasty. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode}, is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

The code for transection of the anterior interosseous nerve (AIN) and/or posterior interosseous nerve (PIN) cannot be reported without an appropriate preoperative diagnosis of chronic pain. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per CMS Payment Policy, use of Platelet Rich Plasma is only reportable as an adjunct to help heal ulcers. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Radical excision bursa, synovia of wrist or forearm tendon sheaths (25115, 25116)
Rationale.RationaleText: Per CPT Assistant June 2012 and the AMA CPT Clinical Vignette for 25115, the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} (Radical excision of bursa, synovia of wrist, or forearm tendon sheaths (eg, tenosynovitis, fungus, Tbc, or other granulomas, rheumatoid arthritis)...) requires documentation of both a radical excision and documentation of a pathological process.
