Thus, a radical excision of bursa, synovia of wrist, or forearm tendon sheaths is not described. Therefore, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Radical resection of bone tumor (Deny and Suggest)
Rationale.RationaleText: Per CPT, radical resection of bone tumors is usually performed for malignant tumors or very aggressive benign tumors and involves resection of the tumor with wide margins of normal tissue. The correct code is chosen based on tumor location, not tumor size or whether the tumor is benign or malignant, primary or metastatic. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and CPT code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT, radical resection of bone tumors is usually performed for malignant tumors or very aggressive benign tumors and involves resection of the tumor with wide margins of normal tissue. If surrounding soft tissue is removed during the procedure, do not report the codes for radical resection of soft tissue tumor separately. Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Radical resection of bone tumor (Not Documented)
Rationale.RationaleText: Per CPT, radical resection of bone tumors is usually performed for malignant tumors or very aggressive benign tumors and involves resection of the tumor with wide margins of normal tissue. This was not described in the operative report submitted for review and thus, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual, Chapter 5, vascular embolization procedures include all associated radiological supervision and interpretation, intra-procedural guidance, road-mapping, and imaging necessary to document completion of the procedure. There is insufficient documentation in the operative report to approve the modifier requested. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Recipient vessel exploration and dissection with microvascular free flap
Rationale.RationaleText: Per American Society of Plastic Surgeons Plastic Surgery News September 1992 and CPT Corner Plastic Surgery News June 2019, ipsilateral vessel exploration, dissection and preparation for recipient sites for a microvascular free flap code are inclusive in the free flap code. Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 6 E. Abdominal Procedures, if a recurrent hernia requires repair, a recurrent hernia repair code may be reported. A code for incisional hernia repair shall not be reported in addition to the recurrent hernia repair code unless a medically necessary incisional hernia repair is performed at a different site. In the latter case, modifier 59 or XS should be used. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per CPT, one cannot report 31267 if he/she exclusively removes tissue from the ostium and not the maxillary sinus itself. Based on the CPT code description (Nasal/sinus endoscopy, surgical, with maxillary antrostomy; with removal of tissue from maxillary sinus); if tissue removal from the ostium occurs during the maxillary antrostomy, but it does not extend into the maxillary sinus, CPT code 31267 is not substantiated and is therefore denied as "Not Documented."

As per the Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons April 2017, the Posterior, or Transversus Abdominus Release Muscular-Fascial flap is another method to mobilize the rectus sheath and muscle, through RELEASE or INCISION of the Transversus Abdominus, in the posterior rectus plane while preserving the neurovascular pedicles. Incisions made to separate the posterior rectus sheath from the rectus muscle in order to place mesh in the retrorectus space without a transversus abdominis release constitutes a Rives-Stoppa repair, not to be coded as 15734. Code 15734 may be reported only when myofascial flaps are created by myofascial releases. A Rives Stoppa repair of a ventral/incisional hernia involves the placement of retrorectus mesh. It is incorrect to report 15734 for a Rives-Stoppa repair. A posterior release or transversus abdominal release involves medializing the rectus muscle via a release of the transversus abdominus in the posterior rectus plane while preserving the neurovascular bundles. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied.

The request for HCPCS code S2900 (Surgical techniques requiring use of robotic surgical system) represents a technique for performing a surgical procedure and therefore is considered included in that procedure. Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Endoscopic Services, a "scout" endoscopy to assess anatomic landmarks or assess extent of disease preceding another surgical procedure at the same patient encounter is not separately reportable. This type of edit may be bypassed only if the 2 procedures are performed on contralateral shoulders." Thus, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 1 C. Medical/Surgical Package, if a definitive surgical procedure requires access through diseased tissue (e.g., necrotic skin, abscess, hematoma, seroma), a separate service for this access (e.g., debridement, incision and drainage) is not separately reportable. As such, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a component service integral to a comprehensive service is not separately reportable. Surgical approach including identification of anatomical landmarks, incision, evaluation of the surgical field, debridement of traumatized tissue, lysis of adhesions, and isolation of structures limiting access to the surgical field such as bone, blood vessels, nerve, and muscles including stimulation for identification or monitoring are considered component services integral to a comprehensive service and therefore, not separately reportable. As such, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a component service integral to a comprehensive service is not separately reportable. Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a component service integral to a comprehensive service is not separately reportable. Surgical cultures and wound irrigation are considered component services integral to a comprehensive service and therefore, not separately reportable. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

As per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 5, Section D Cardiovascular, Number 26, removal of thrombus from the vascular territory of a vessel treated with an atherectomy is inherent in the work of the atherectomy procedure. The thrombectomy procedure (37184 - 37186) is not separately reportable for removal of such thrombus. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as Not Documented.

Rationale.RationaleText: Per American Academy of Otolaryngology-Head and Neck Surgery Policy 2020, Removal of "tissue" means polyps, fungus ball, mucocoele, etc., and NOT "debris" or "pus". Removal must be from within the sinus (not at the ostium or creating the "ostomy"). Thus, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, the treatment of a complication of a primary surgical procedure is not separately reportable if it represents usual and necessary care in the operating room during the procedure; or if it occurs postoperatively and does not require return to the operating room. For example, control of hemorrhage is a usual and necessary component of a surgical procedure in the operating room and is not separately reportable. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, a physician shall not unbundle services that are integral to a more comprehensive procedure. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to the primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, physicians must report Units of Service (UOS) correctly. The narrative report is insufficient to support the UOS requested. A physician shall not report UOS for a CPT code using a criterion that differs from the code's defined unit of service. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, if a physician provides a service that is not accurately described by other CPT codes, the service shall be reported using an unlisted procedure code. A physician shall not report a CPT code for a specific procedure if it does not accurately describe the service performed. It is inappropriate to report the best fit CPT code unless it accurately describes the service performed, and all components of the CPT code were performed. Thus, the requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and unlisted procedure code {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I General Correct Coding Policies, if a physician provides a service that is not accurately described by other CPT codes, the service shall be reported using an unlisted procedure code. A physician shall not report a CPT code for a specific procedure if it does not accurately describe the service performed. It is inappropriate to report the best fit CPT code unless it accurately describes the service performed, and all components of the CPT code were performed. Thus, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 5 D. Cardiovascular System, Replacement of a ventricular assist device (VAD) includes removal of the old pump, insertion of a new pump, and initiation of the new pump. CPT codes describing implantation (insertion) or removal of a VAD shall not be reported separately with a CPT code describing replacement of a VAD. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

As per the Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons April 2017, If a hernia repair is performed at the site of an incision for an open or laparoscopic abdominal procedure, the hernia repair is inherently inclusive, and not separately reported. When the laparoscopic trocar port is placed through the hernia with subsequent closure of the hernia port site, only the open procedure, or, the laparoscopic abdominal procedure is reported. As such, the request for ventral hernia repair may not be reported with an open or laparoscopic abdominal procedure performed through the umbilical, peri-umbilical, ventral abdominal incision, or incisional scar associated with the hernia being repaired. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4, when closure of umbilical, ventral or incisional hernia is accomplished by closure of midline incision without need for separate dissection and repair, the hernia repair codes are include in the primary procedure code(s). Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual, when closure of umbilical, ventral or incisional hernia is accomplished by closure of midline incision without need for separate dissection and repair, the hernia repair codes are included in the primary procedure code(s). Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: Voiding Pressure Study Using a Penile Cuff
Rationale.RationaleText: The American Urological Association recommends that practices verify what code the insurance company will accept for the penile cuff. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied and {SuggestedCode} is suggested.

Per CPT, in requested service code, 26145 Synovectomy, tendon sheath, radical (tenosynovectomy), flexor tendon, palm and/or finger, each tendon, the physician removes the synovial membrane from a flexor tendon sheath (tenosynovectomy) at the palm or finger. The sheath is excised, except for a small area in the middle of the phalanx sections and the synovium is removed as much as possible. CPT code 29875 shall not be reported with another arthroscopic knee procedure on the ipsilateral knee. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to primary procedure code {IncludedCode}.

Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 E. Arthroscopy, CPT code 29876 may only be reported for a clinically indicated synovectomy with another arthroscopic knee procedure if the synovectomy is performed in two compartments on which another arthroscopic procedure is not performed. The clinical indications for appropriate use, are defined by AAOS Now January 2013, which states that the synovium must be pathological (RA, gout, PVN, infection, chondrocalcinosis). The operative report submitted for review does not document any proliferative, diseased synovium. As such, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

As per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter 4 E. Arthroscopy, AAOS Now February/March 2018 and AAOS Now January 2011, the requested CPT code, 29876 (Arthroscopy, knee, surgical; synovectomy, major, 2 or more compartments) may only be reported for synovectomy with another arthroscopic knee procedure if the synovectomy is performed in two compartments on which another arthroscopic procedure is not performed. In addition, AAOS Now February/March 2018 states that 29876 "should not be used for a cleanup of hypertrophic synovium. It is to be used only when the synovium has an underlying pathology such as rheumatoid arthritis or pigmented villonodular synovitis." Thus, CPT code 29876 is not described in the submitted material and is denied as "Not Documented."

If a separate pathologic diagnosis such as rheumatoid arthritis or tenosynovitis is present, and a flexor tenosynovectomy is performed, code 25115, Radical excision of bursa, synovia of wrist, or forearm tendon sheaths (eg, tenosynovitis, fungus, Tbc, or other granulomas, rheumatoid arthritis); flexors, would be reported in addition to 64721 Neuroplasty and/or transposition; median nerve at carpal tunnel. Therefore, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

The requested CPT code 29823 (Arthroscopy, shoulder, surgical; debridement, extensive) is not described. Portions of the described procedure are most consistent with an arthroscopic shoulder synovectomy. Arthroscopic synovectomy (partial, complete) CPT codes (29820, 29821) are NCCI Procedure-to-Procedure Edits with one or more approved primary procedure code(s). Thus, the synovectomy portion of the described surgery is included in the primary procedure. CPT code 29823 requires extensive debridement of 3 or more discrete structures (eg, humeral bone, humeral articular cartilage, glenoid bone, glenoid articular cartilage, biceps tendon, biceps anchor complex, labrum, articular capsule, articular side of the rotator cuff, bursal side of the rotator cuff, subacromial bursa, foreign body[ies]). In addition, per CPT Assistant December 2020: "As with all other arthroscopic debridement codes, it is important to note that the structures debrided as part of another procedure reported for the same session cannot be counted to meet the criteria of the debridement code." Debridement of 3 or more discrete structures where no other work was performed is not documented. Therefore, the request for {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented." AAOS Now February/March 2018 states arthroscopic synovectomy "should not be used for a cleanup of hypertrophic synovium. It is to be used only when the synovium has an underlying pathology such as rheumatoid arthritis or pigmented villonodular synovitis." Thus, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is not described in the submitted material and is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, when the work required to provide a service is substantially greater than typically required, it may be identified by adding modifier 22 to the usual procedure code. Documentation must support the substantial additional work and the reason for the additional work (i.e., increased intensity, time, technical difficulty of procedure, and severity of patient's condition, physical and mental effort required). The clinical documentation submitted for review does not support the substantial additional work and the reason for the additional work. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode}-22 is denied as "Not Documented".

Appropriate use of Modifier 22 requires documentation of a substantial increase of time and effort required to perform the procedure. Since this was not documented in the operative report submitted for review, the request for Modifier 22 cannot be approved. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode}-22 is denied as "Not Documented".

As per the Bulletin of the American College of Surgeons April 2017, incisions made to separate the posterior rectus sheath from the rectus muscle in order to place mesh in the retrorectus space without a transversus abdominis release constitutes a Rives-Stoppa repair. It is not to be coded as 15734. Code 15734 may be reported only when myofascial flaps are created by myofascial releases. A Rives Stoppa repair of a ventral/incisional hernia involves the placement of retrorectus mesh. It is incorrect to report 15734 for a Rives-Stoppa repair. A posterior release or transversus abdominal release involves medializing the rectus muscle via a release of the transversus abdominus in the posterior rectus plane while preserving the neurovascular bundles. In an anterior component separation technique, an anterior release mobilizes the entire rectus sheath toward the midline by incising the aponeurosis of the external oblique from the costal margin to the inguinal ligament." As such the requested CPT 15734 is denied as "Not Documented".

The procedure described in the submitted operative report does not involve a significant length of the deep or superficial femoral artery, or external iliac artery and thus is most consistent with a common femoral endarterectomy. As such, the requested service code {ServiceCode} is denied and CPT code {35371} is suggested.

Per CPT, unlike the open skull base surgery codes that include separate codes for the approach and definitive procedure, CPT code 62165 includes the approach, tumor resection and closure. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to CPT code 62165.

Per CPT, the requested service code, 95865, is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is, therefore, denied as "Not Documented." The clinical documentation provided does not sufficiently describe or support the requisite criteria for approval of diagnostic needle electromyography; larynx (including recording during needle insertion). As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per NCCI Policy Manual, Chapter 4, (General Policy Statement #10): "Exploration of the surgical field is a standard surgical practice. Physicians shall not report a CPT code describing exploration of a surgical field with another CPT code describing a procedure in that surgical field." Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as inclusive to {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleText: The narrative operative report included with the clinical documentation is illegible and/or incomplete. Therefore, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, under certain circumstances a service or procedure is partially reduced or eliminated at the discretion of the physician. Under these circumstances the service provided can be identified by its usual CPT code and the addition of modifier 52, signifying that the service is reduced. This provides a means of reporting reduced services without disturbing the identification of the basic service. Review of the operative/procedure report suggests that a reduced level of service was provided in this case. As such, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied.

As per the CMS National Physician Fee Schedule (NPFS), the requested service code {ServiceCode} has a payment policy indicator of 0. As such, payment restriction for assistants at surgery applies to this procedure unless supporting documentation is submitted to establish medical necessity.  Insufficient supporting documentation is submitted to establish medical necessity.   Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as not eligible for assistant surgeon reimbursement.

Per CPT Assistant 2005 and CPT Knowledge Base 2002, code 23420 describes a repair of a complete shoulder (rotator) cuff avulsion, referring to the repair of all three major muscles/tendons of the shoulder cuff. This type of significant tear usually requires rearrangement of the normal anatomy and sometimes grafting with either biological or nonbiological material for repair. In addition, as per the American Academy of Orthopedic Surgeons, 23420 should be reported when the surgeon reconstructs a massive rotator cuff tear requiring extensive releases and mobilization of tissue. This degree of surgery is not described in the operative report. Thus, CPT code 23420 (Reconstruction of complete shoulder (rotator) cuff avulsion, chronic (includes acromioplasty)) is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT Assistant March 2008, CPT code 29827 (arthroscopy, shoulder, surgical; with rotator cuff repair) "represents the repair of one, two or three tendons and the number of portals made does not alter the use of this particular code. When another portal is required to repair the subscapularis tendon, it is considered an inclusive component of the procedure." The operative report does not describe the degree of substantial additional work consistent with Modifier 22 and thus the request for Modifier 22 cannot be approved. Thus, CPT code 29827-22 is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT and the AMA CPT Clinical Vignette for code 23615 (Open treatment of proximal humeral (surgical or anatomical neck) fracture, includes internal fixation, when performed, includes repair of tuberosity(s), when performed) states: "The fracture fragments (parts) are evaluated and reduced. The reduction including the tuberosities is often complex requiring reduction of fragments one to another and then reduction of the larger fragments…Often an interfragmentary screw or reduction K wires are required to maintain the reduction while plates or screws are placed to stabilize the fracture. Multiple plating and screw configurations are possible. Once the fracture is reduced and secured with plate and screws the wound is copiously irrigated with antibiotic saline." The surgical procedure described in the submitted operative report is not consistent with this type of open fracture treatment. Therefore, the request for 23615 is denied as "Not Documented".

Per CPT, the requested service code, 29867 (Arthroscopy, knee, surgical; osteochondral allograft (eg, mosaicplasty)) is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented." Consistent with the guidance from CPT Assistant, April 2019, unless an actual osteochondral allograft is used and defects are filled with osteochondral allograft customized to fit the defect, it is not appropriate to report code 29867. Thus, the surgery described in the submitted operative report is inconsistent with CPT code 29867 and is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode} (Fasciectomy, partial palmar with release of single digit including proximal interphalangeal joint), is not described in the operative report submitted for review. Per CPT Descriptor, CPT Assistant May 2021 and CPT AMA Vignette for 26123, a fasciectomy for a diseased or pathologic fascial cord (eg, Dupuytren's contracture) including proximal interphalangeal joint is not described. Therefore, the request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, 26121 (Fasciectomy, palm only, with or without Z-plasty, other local tissue rearrangement, or skin grafting) is not described in the operative report submitted for review. Consistent with the guidance from CPT Assistant May 2021 and CPT AMA Vignette for 26123,a fasciectomy for a diseased or pathologic fascial cord (eg, Dupuytren's contracture) is not described. Therefore, the request for CPT code 26121 is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, 15769 [Grafting of autologous soft tissue, other, harvested by direct excision (eg, fat, dermis, fascia)] is not described in the operative report submitted for review. Per CPT Assistant October 2019, "Code 15769 describes autologous soft tissue grafts, such as fat, dermis, fascia, or other soft tissues, which are harvested via direct excision from a donor site and then placed into a defect in a separate recipient site during the same operative session." This degree of surgery is not described in the operative report. Thus, the request for CPT code 15769 is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented." For the CPT requested, 45385, the operative report does not specifically state if the snare was used to remove or retrieve the same polyp(s) already excised by the forceps at same endoscopic setting, or if the snare was used to excise ADDITIONAL polyp(s) from a DIFFERENT anatomc site(s). CPT 45385 cannot be billed separately if used to remove or retrieve polyp(s) already excised by forceps.

CPT 15734 specifically refers to a muscular or fascial flap, based on a vascular pedicle, identified by the donor site(not the recipient site), in order to obliterate an anatomic defect. The prepared flap is rotated from the donor area to the site needing repair, and sutured into place. The donor area is closed primarily. Reporting of CPT code 15734 requires that the flap (muscle or other tissue) is mobilized, isolated on its primary or secondary blood supply and then transferred locally or regionally. The operative report does not support these criteria, and therefore, the request for 15734 is denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, the requested service code, 11960, is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented." Per CPT Changes 2021: "A parenthetical note has been added following code 11960 to instruct users on the appropriate reporting for tissue expanders. Code 11960 is used to report the placement of tissue expanders that are left in place and expanded over time to increase soft tissue. To avoid misreporting of tissue expander codes, the exclusionary parenthetical note has been established to instruct users not to report 11960 with codes 11971, 13160, 29848, and 64702-64726. In addition, rationale In support of the addition of a parenthetical note following code 11960 to report the placement of tissue expanders, an exclusionary parenthetical note has been added following code 29848 to preclude reporting code 29848 in conjunction with code 11960.

Per CPT, for bypass graft codes 35501 - 35571 and 35601 - 35671, establishing both inflow and outflow by any method is included in the bypass graft code. Per NCCI Policy, if a bypass graft procedure requires an additional procedure and/or intervention to establish inflow and/or outflow, to insert the graft, only the code describing the bypass graft may be reported. The additional procedure is not separately reportable since it is a component service. Therefore, requested CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

The requested service code, {ServiceCode}, has already been reviewed on another service line in this claim. As such, this request for CPT code {ServiceCode} is considered a "Duplicate" and is denied as "Not Documented." X units are the maximum number of units allowed by the Medically Unlikely Edits for this CPT code, and these have been approved elsewhere in the claim.

Per CPT, the requested service code, {ServiceCode}, is not substantiated by the clinical documentation submitted for review and is therefore, denied as "Not Documented." A revascularization procedure consistent with CPT {ServiceCode} is not clearly described.

Per CPT, 35371 thromboendarterectomy includes patch graft, if performed; common femoral. Unless the procedure involves a significant length of the deep or superficial femoral artery, or external iliac artery, report only the common femoral procedure (35371). The operative report submitted for review describes a common femoral endarterectomy. As such, the requested service code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."

Rationale.RationaleSummary: No Thrombectomy During Catheter Change/Removal (INCLUSIVE DENIAL)
Rationale.RationaleText: Per NCCI Policy Manual Chapter I, "A physician shall not unbundle services that are integral to a more comprehensive procedure."  Therefore, in this clinical situation, the service described by CPT {ServiceCode} is integral to the comprehensive service, CPT code {IncludedCode}.   Balloon maceration of non-obstructive thrombus during concomitant balloon angioplasty to treat a fibrin sheath and/or venous stenosis is included in the primary procedure.  As such, the request for component service, CPT code {ServiceCode}, is denied as inclusive to comprehensive service, CPT code {IncludedCode}.

Rationale.RationaleSummary: No Thrombectomy During Catheter Change/Removal (NOT DOCUMENTED)
Rationale.RationaleText: The operative report supports a primary procedure, which when coded correctly, includes the requested service CPT code {ServiceCode}. Balloon maceration of non-obstructive thrombus during concomitant balloon angioplasty to treat a fibrin sheath and/or venous stenosis would be included in the primary procedure when coded correctly.  Therefore, the services described by CPT code {ServiceCode} would be considered inclusive to the correctly coded primary procedure and as such could not be approved separately and thus, are denied as "Not Documented."

Per CPT, code 99153 Moderate sedation services provided by the same physician or other qualified health care professional performing the diagnostic or therapeutic service that the sedation supports, each additional 15 minutes intraservice time; includes monitoring of the patient's response to drugs and vital signs. The clinical documentation provided does not sufficiently describe or support the requisite criteria for approval of the requested CPT code. As such, CPT code {ServiceCode} is denied as "Not Documented."
